elements.description:
A calendar element using Polymer.

If you like to connect it to an input, try it like:

  ```html
    <input type="date" value="{{date::input}}">

    <calendar-element date="{{date}}"></calendar-element>
  ```

The following custom properties and mixins are also available for styling:

Custom property | Description | Default
----------------|-------------|----------
`--datetime-background` | text-color of the time-element | `#252525`
`--datetime-color` | text-color of the time-element | `#ccc`
`--datetime-selected-background` | background-color of the focussed time-input and the hovered icons | `--primary-color, #253EEC`
`--datetime-selected-color` | color of the focussed time-input and the hovered icons | `#f1f1f1`
`--datetime-element` | Mixin applied to the time-element and the calender-element | `{}`
`--datetime-input` | Mixin applied to the inputs | {border-radius: 2px; padding: 0.35em; border: none; outline: none; text-align: center; box-sizing: content-box; background-color: transparent; transition: background-color 150ms cubic-bezier(0.6, 1, 0.2, 1);}`
`--datetime-icon` | Mixin applied to closing icon | `{padding: 8px; height: 16px; transition: background-color 150ms cubic-bezier(0.6, 1, 0.2, 1); fill: currentColor;}`

elements.description:
`time-element`

A polyfill time picker using Polymer.

If you like to connect it to an input, try it like:

 ```html
    <input type="time" value="{{time::input}}" step="1">

    <time-element time="{{time}}"></time-element>
 ```

Custom property | Description | Default

`--datetime-color` | text-color of the time-element | `#ccc`
`--datetime-selected-background` | background-color of the focussed time-input and the hovered icons | `--primary-color, #253EEC`
`--datetime-selected-color` | color of the focussed time-input and the hovered icons | `#f1f1f1`
`--datetime-element` | Mixin applied to the time-element and the calender-element | `{}`
`--datetime-input` | Mixin applied to the inputs | {border-radius: 2px; padding: 0.35em; border: none; outline: none; text-align: center; box-sizing: content-box; background-color: transparent; transition: background-color 150ms cubic-bezier(0.6, 1, 0.2, 1);}`
`--datetime-icon` | Mixin applied to closing icon | `{padding: 8px; height: 16px; transition: background-color 150ms cubic-bezier(0.6, 1, 0.2, 1); fill: currentColor;}`

elements.description:
`datetime-picker` is a picker for date and time for **[Polymer](https://github.com/Polymer/polymer)** that prefers to use the native input. This element is for using the *native* date-picker, if it exists, or to replace it by a CustomElement. The `calendar-element` and the `time-element` will just be used if the native picker is not available or is explicitly wanted.

 ```html
   <datetime-picker value="{{value}}"></datetime-picker>
 ```

 If you need an **overlay** then use `overlay-datetime-picker`, what extends `datetime-picker` and create the polyfilled elements `time-element` and `calendar-element` in an `overlay-element`, that extends *IronOverlayBehavior* and will create some of its attribute-bindings.


 Custom property | Description | Default
 ----------------|-------------|----------
 `--datetime-background` | text-color of the time-element | `#252525`
 `--datetime-color` | text-color of the time-element | `#ccc`
 `--datetime-selected-background` | background-color of the focussed time-input and the hovered icons | `--primary-color, #253EEC`
 `--datetime-selected-color` | color of the focussed time-input and the hovered icons | `#f1f1f1`
 `--datetime-element` | Mixin applied to the time-element and the calender-element | `{}`
 `--datetime-input` | Mixin applied to the inputs | {border-radius: 2px; padding: 0.35em; border: none; outline: none; text-align: center; box-sizing: content-box; background-color: transparent; transition: background-color 150ms cubic-bezier(0.6, 1, 0.2, 1);}`
 `--datetime-icon` | Mixin applied to closing icon | `{padding: 8px; height: 16px; transition: background-color 150ms cubic-bezier(0.6, 1, 0.2, 1); fill: currentColor;}`
 `--datetime-native-input` | Mixin applied to the native inputs of the datetime-picker| `{}`

elements.description:
`overlay-element`
A helper-element, that creates an overlay using iron-overlay-behavior of Polymer.

properties.name: sizingTarget
properties.description:
The element that will receive a `max-height`/`width`. By default it is the same as `this`,
but it can be set to a child element. This is useful, for example, for implementing a
scrolling region inside the element.

properties.name: fitInto
properties.description: The element to fit `this` into.

properties.name: noOverlap
properties.description: Will position the element around the positionTarget without overlapping it.

properties.name: positionTarget
properties.description:
The element that should be used to position the element. If not set, it will
default to the parent node.

properties.name: horizontalAlign
properties.description:
The orientation against which to align the element horizontally
relative to the `positionTarget`. Possible values are "left", "right", "auto".

properties.name: verticalAlign
properties.description:
The orientation against which to align the element vertically
relative to the `positionTarget`. Possible values are "top", "bottom", "auto".

properties.name: dynamicAlign
properties.description:
If true, it will use `horizontalAlign` and `verticalAlign` values as preferred alignment
and if there's not enough space, it will pick the values which minimize the cropping.

properties.name: horizontalOffset
properties.description:
A pixel value that will be added to the position calculated for the
given `horizontalAlign`, in the direction of alignment. You can think
of it as increasing or decreasing the distance to the side of the
screen given by `horizontalAlign`.

If `horizontalAlign` is "left", this offset will increase or decrease
the distance to the left side of the screen: a negative offset will
move the dropdown to the left; a positive one, to the right.

Conversely if `horizontalAlign` is "right", this offset will increase
or decrease the distance to the right side of the screen: a negative
offset will move the dropdown to the right; a positive one, to the left.

properties.name: verticalOffset
properties.description:
A pixel value that will be added to the position calculated for the
given `verticalAlign`, in the direction of alignment. You can think
of it as increasing or decreasing the distance to the side of the
screen given by `verticalAlign`.

If `verticalAlign` is "top", this offset will increase or decrease
the distance to the top side of the screen: a negative offset will
move the dropdown upwards; a positive one, downwards.

Conversely if `verticalAlign` is "bottom", this offset will increase
or decrease the distance to the bottom side of the screen: a negative
offset will move the dropdown downwards; a positive one, upwards.

properties.name: autoFitOnAttach
properties.description: Set to true to auto-fit on attach.

properties.name: _parentResizable
properties.description: The closest ancestor element that implements `IronResizableBehavior`.

properties.name: _notifyingDescendant
properties.description:
True if this element is currently notifying its descendant elements of
resize.

properties.name: opened
properties.description: True if the overlay is currently displayed.

properties.name: canceled
properties.description: True if the overlay was canceled when it was last closed.

properties.name: withBackdrop
properties.description:
Set to true to display a backdrop behind the overlay. It traps the focus
within the light DOM of the overlay.

properties.name: noAutoFocus
properties.description:
Set to true to disable auto-focusing the overlay or child nodes with
the `autofocus` attribute` when the overlay is opened.

properties.name: noCancelOnEscKey
properties.description: Set to true to disable canceling the overlay with the ESC key.

properties.name: noCancelOnOutsideClick
properties.description: Set to true to disable canceling the overlay by clicking outside it.

properties.name: closingReason
properties.description:
Contains the reason(s) this overlay was last closed (see `iron-overlay-closed`).
`IronOverlayBehavior` provides the `canceled` reason; implementers of the
behavior can provide other reasons in addition to `canceled`.

properties.name: restoreFocusOnClose
properties.description: Set to true to enable restoring of focus when overlay is closed.

properties.name: alwaysOnTop
properties.description: Set to true to keep overlay always on top.

properties.name: _manager
properties.description: Shortcut to access to the overlay manager.

properties.name: _focusedChild
properties.description: The node being focused.

methods.name: _defaultPositionTarget
methods.description:
The element that should be used to position the element,
if no position target is configured.

methods.name: _localeHorizontalAlign
methods.description: The horizontal align value, accounting for the RTL/LTR text direction.

methods.name: fit
methods.description: Positions and fits the element into the `fitInto` element.

methods.name: _discoverInfo
methods.description: Memoize information needed to position and size the target element.

methods.name: resetFit
methods.description:
Resets the target element's position and size constraints, and clear
the memoized data.

methods.name: refit
methods.description:
Equivalent to calling `resetFit()` and `fit()`. Useful to call this after
the element or the `fitInto` element has been resized, or if any of the
positioning properties (e.g. `horizontalAlign, verticalAlign`) is updated.
It preserves the scroll position of the sizingTarget.

methods.name: position
methods.description: Positions the element according to `horizontalAlign, verticalAlign`.

methods.name: constrain
methods.description:
Constrains the size of the element to `fitInto` by setting `max-height`
and/or `max-width`.

methods.name: center
methods.description:
Centers horizontally and vertically if not already positioned. This also sets
`position:fixed`.

methods.name: notifyResize
methods.description:
Can be called to manually notify a resizable and its descendant
resizables of a resize change.

methods.name: assignParentResizable
methods.description:
Used to assign the closest resizable ancestor to this resizable
if the ancestor detects a request for notifications.

methods.name: stopResizeNotificationsFor
methods.description:
Used to remove a resizable descendant from the list of descendants
that should be notified of a resize change.

methods.name: resizerShouldNotify
methods.description:
This method can be overridden to filter nested elements that should or
should not be notified by the current element. Return true if an element
should be notified, or false if it should not be notified.

params.name: element
params.description:
A candidate descendant element that
implements `IronResizableBehavior`.

return.desc: True if the `element` should be notified of resize.

methods.name: backdropElement
methods.description: The backdrop element.

methods.name: _focusNode
methods.description: Returns the node to give focus to.

methods.name: _focusableNodes
methods.description:
Array of nodes that can receive focus (overlay included), ordered by `tabindex`.
This is used to retrieve which is the first and last focusable nodes in order
to wrap the focus for overlays `with-backdrop`.

If you know what is your content (specifically the first and last focusable children),
you can override this method to return only `[firstFocusable, lastFocusable];`

methods.name: toggle
methods.description: Toggle the opened state of the overlay.

methods.name: open
methods.description: Open the overlay.

methods.name: close
methods.description: Close the overlay.

methods.name: cancel
methods.description: Cancels the overlay.

methods.name: invalidateTabbables
methods.description:
Invalidates the cached tabbable nodes. To be called when any of the focusable
content changes (e.g. a button is disabled).

methods.name: _openedChanged
methods.description: Called when `opened` changes.

methods.name: _prepareRenderOpened
methods.description: tasks which must occur before opening; e.g. making the element visible.

methods.name: _renderOpened
methods.description: Tasks which cause the overlay to actually open; typically play an animation.

methods.name: _renderClosed
methods.description: Tasks which cause the overlay to actually close; typically play an animation.

methods.name: _finishRenderOpened
methods.description: Tasks to be performed at the end of open action. Will fire `iron-overlay-opened`.

methods.name: _finishRenderClosed
methods.description: Tasks to be performed at the end of close action. Will fire `iron-overlay-closed`.

methods.name: _applyFocus
methods.description: Applies focus according to the opened state.

methods.name: _onCaptureClick
methods.description: Cancels (closes) the overlay. Call when click happens outside the overlay.

methods.name: _onCaptureFocus
methods.description: Keeps track of the focused child. If withBackdrop, traps focus within overlay.

methods.name: _onCaptureEsc
methods.description: Handles the ESC key event and cancels (closes) the overlay.

methods.name: _onCaptureTab
methods.description:
Handles TAB key events to track focus changes.
Will wrap focus for overlays withBackdrop.

methods.name: _onIronResize
methods.description: Refits if the overlay is opened and not animating.

methods.name: _onNodesChange
methods.description:
Will call notifyResize if overlay is opened.
Can be overridden in order to avoid multiple observers on the same node.

methods.name: __ensureFirstLastFocusables
methods.description: Will set first and last focusable nodes if any of them is not set.

methods.name: __openedChanged
methods.description:
Tasks executed when opened changes: prepare for the opening, move the
focus, update the manager, render opened/closed.

methods.name: __onNextAnimationFrame
methods.description:
Executes a callback on the next animation frame, overriding any previous
callback awaiting for the next animation frame. e.g.
`__onNextAnimationFrame(callback1) && __onNextAnimationFrame(callback2)`;
`callback1` will never be invoked.

params.name: callback
params.description: Its `this` parameter is the overlay itself.

elements.description:
`date-picker` is a picker for date for **[Polymer](https://github.com/Polymer/polymer)** that prefers to use the native input. This element is for using the *native* date-picker, if it exists, or to replace it by a CustomElement. The `calendar-element` and the `time-element` will just be used if the native picker is not available or is explicitly wanted.

 ```html
   <date-picker value="{{value}}"></date-picker>
 ```

 If you need an **overlay** then use `overlay-date-picker`, what extends `date-picker` and create the `calendar-element` in an `overlay-element`, that extends *IronOverlayBehavior* and will create some of its attribute-bindings.


 Custom property | Description | Default
 ----------------|-------------|----------
 `--datetime-background` | text-color of the time-element | `#252525`
 `--datetime-color` | text-color of the time-element | `#ccc`
 `--datetime-selected-background` | background-color of the focussed time-input and the hovered icons | `--primary-color, #253EEC`
 `--datetime-selected-color` | color of the focussed time-input and the hovered icons | `#f1f1f1`
 `--datetime-element` | Mixin applied to the time-element and the calender-element | `{}`
 `--datetime-input` | Mixin applied to the inputs | {border-radius: 2px; padding: 0.35em; border: none; outline: none; text-align: center; box-sizing: content-box; background-color: transparent; transition: background-color 150ms cubic-bezier(0.6, 1, 0.2, 1);}`
 `--datetime-icon` | Mixin applied to closing icon | `{padding: 8px; height: 16px; transition: background-color 150ms cubic-bezier(0.6, 1, 0.2, 1); fill: currentColor;}`
